{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_emmental_ver01/data/sn83045293/00517012452/1920111901/0330.xml":{"full_text":"TWO\n2,242 CITY EMPLOYES HERE THREATENED WITH SHAKEUP\nDEPARTMENTS ARE\nTOP-HEAVY, STATES\nSERVICE CHIEFTAIN\nFour Months\u2019 Study of Subjects Show Need for Houseclean\ning, Says Peter J. Koehler to Common\nCouncil Committee.\nCITY BOARD MEMBERS TO CONSIDER CHANGES\nA \u201chouse cleaning\u201d today\nthreatened the 2,242 employes of\nthe various departments of the\nMilwaukee city service, following\ncharges that many of them are\n\u201ctop-heavy,\u201d voiced by Peter J.\nKoehler, president, civil service\ncommission, before the common\ncouncil finance committee, late\nyesterday.\nwants City Shakeup.\nKoehler urged the committee to\npromote a \u201cshakeup\u201d to eliminate\nwhat he styled unnecessary em\nployes in various departments in\nthe' interest of efficiency and econ\nomv. He said his statements weie\nbased on the disclosures of a four\nmonths' study of all tl^e positions in\nthe city service.\nHe explained he and Commis\nsioner Fred Heise were, designated\nby the commission to take charge\nof the investigation, decided upon\nto provide information considered\nfundamental in the preparation of a\ntentative city employes salary sched\nule. requested by the council.\nAlthough they made no definite\nannouncement of their attitude, fol\nlowing Koehler\u2019s charges, the mem\nbers of the finance committee inti\nmated they would devote particular\nattention to them, as they went into\nexecutive session to consider the\nsalary schedule, position by position.\nHoppe Joins Koehler.\nCommissioner Otto Hoppe joined\nCommissioner Koehler and Heise in\ndefense of the schedule their or\nganization prepared, under which\n1.639 employes are recommended\nfor increases, and 86 for decreases,\nwhile the remaining 517 experience\nno change in salary.\nKoehler informed the cost of liv\ning was not taken into considera\ntion, in connection with the posi\ntions recoinmended for salary re\nductions and that the commission\u2019s\nconclusion was based on the duties\nof the positions and salaries being\npaid for similar work in privately\noperated establishments.\nAllow Jobs to Pile Up.\nHe declared the city government\u2019s\npolicy for many years has been\nsuch ns to allow new positions to\npile up in the various departments\nand expressed the opinion a yearly\ncheck up is necessary if the em\nployes are to be kept down to the\nnumber whose services are really\nrequired. He said:\nMy four months\u2019 study of the\ncity service convinced me that\nmany of its departments are top-\nWavy. In many of the depart\nments there are employes whose\nservices could be dispensed with,\nwithout impairing the efficiency.\n\"it- would seem that the heads of\ndepartments would be conscious\nof such situations, but perhaps\nthey have not been impressed,\nowing to the fact they have be\ncome accustomed to them.\n\u201cHide Behind Book.\u201d\nThe hardest job some city em\nployes have is to hide behind a\nbook and maintain a watch to\nmake sure that the head of the\ndepartment does not catch them\nloafing.\nKoehler justified the proposed re\nduction from SBS to S6O in the\nmonthly salary of women in the city\nhall janitorial service, by recom\nmending that their five hours\u2019 serv\nice should be in a continuous\nstretch, instead of having them\nwork from 6 to 8 a. m. and from 5\nto 8 p. m. and forcing them to use\nfour street car tickets each day. He\ncharacterized as \"nonsensical\u201d the\nmorning and night shifts for these\nwomen and said they should be em\nployed from 5 to 10 p. m.\nINTER-COLLEGIATE PRESS\nASSN. WILL MEET HERE\nDECEMBER 3RD TO 4TH\nMarquette university and Milwau\nkee Downer college will entertain\ntire Wisconsin Inter-College Press\nAssn. at its second annual conven\ntion in Miwaukee, Dec. 3 and 4.\nThis convention will consist of the\nformal opening at Marquette, a\nround table for the delegates and\nfaculty of the schools, a trip to the\nlocal newsnaper offices, a luncheon\nSaturday followed by election of of\nficers and theater party Saturday\nevening for delegates who remain\nin Milwaukee until Sunday.\nThe purpose of the Inter-College\nPress Assn., founded at Madison\nlast year, is the advancement of the\ncause of college journalism. Its\ncharter members are the following\nWisconsin schools: Carroll. Beloit,\nRipon, Lawrence, St. Mary\u2019s. Milwau\nkee Downer. Milton, Northland, the\n1 niversity of Wisconsin, Marquette,\nCampion and St. Clara\u2019s.\nBUSINESS SLUMP\nCUTS MS BONUS\nMany Firms to Abandon An\nnual Gift Practice.\nBusiness depression today was\nblamed by Phil A. Grau, business\nmanager, Commerce Assn., for the\ndiscontinuance of paying Christmas\nbonuses by manufacturing firms to\nemployes this year.\n\u201cThere is no doubt that the re\ncent business depression in many\nlines has prompted employers to\nforesake the giving of the bonuses\nas Christmas gifts,\u2019\u2019 he said.\nVery few firms will give bonuses\nthis year.\nThe Bartles-Magurie Oil Co. and\nthe Allis-Chalmers Co. have defl\n*ltely decided to abandon the an\nnual award while officials of the\nCutler-Hammer Co., Pawling Hur\nnlachfeger Co. and the Columbia\nKnitting Co. asserted that they havo\nnot decided the question yet, al\nthough in times past it had been\ndefinitely decided by this time.\nFriday, November 19, 1920.\nj Charles Munkwitz\n96 Years Old Today]\nCharles J. Munkwitz. pioneer Mil\nwaukeean. celebrated his 96th birth-\nn home,\nJuneau Pl.,\n\u2022<today.\nMunkwitz was\nfc born near Leipsig,\nSaxony, Nov. 19,\n1824. He came to\nWk N ew York city\n8 1848 and\nremoved to Mil\nwaukee in August,\n184 8. Before r e\ntiring from active\nbusiness life more\n!>sWMBa3 'than 30 years\nago, ne was engaged in a retail\nmeat business. Mason St. and Broad\nway, and several otner locations\nlater.\nMunkwitz is in the best of health\nand enjoys long walks every day.\n\u2018VFESENTENCE\nFOR AUTO THEFT\nIS TOO DRASTIC\u201d\nPropaganda More Effective,\nSafety Members Say.\nPropaganda and strict legislation\nwill go further toward the reduction\nof automobile thefts than drastic\nmethods, such as life imprisonment\nor the death penalty, as discussed in\nChicago, for this would be nothing\nmore than the return of au\ntocratic days of the dark ages, ac\ncording to members of the Milwau\nkee safety commission.\n\u201cThe best suggestion I have seen\nso far is the one made in Milwaukee\nof licensing all drivers, which W. J.\nof licensing all drivers,\u201d said W. J.\nC. Flieth today. \u201cThis will make it\npossible for a policeman to stop any\nperson driving a car and demand his\nlicense. This life imprisonment or\ndeath penalty for the theft of a car\nis primitive.\u201d\n\u201cIf we had all drivers of cars in\nMilwaukee licensed as advocated,\nthefts would be different because a\ndriver would have to show his license\non request,\u201d declared Claude Diegle,\nsecretary of the \u2019Milwaukee safety\ncommission. \u201cThis propaganda for\nlife sentence or death penalty for the\ntheft of a car is throwing us back to\nthe, dark days of middle ages. We\ncan accomplish more by propaganda,\nand strict rulings than by any other\nmethod.\u201d\nAccording to John Anderson of\nthe T. M. E. R. L. Co., the li\ncensing of drivers would do away\nlargely with the thefts and that t the\ndeath penalty or life ihaprisonment\nis far too severe for the crime.\nPERMITS HEATAS\nCHIRM RENT\nRuling Does Not Affect \u201cCoal\nin Bin\u201d Order.\nThe rail commission today upheld\na landlord\u2019s policy of charging\nhigher rent during the winter when\ncoal is being used.\nJ. L. Streeter, 368 Cass St., had\nfiled a complaint against M. J.\nReiley, owner, stating he was\ncharged $45 a month for his apart\nment from Oct. 1 to May 1, and $35\na month for the five months from\nMay 1 to Oct. 1. On claim of\nReiley that use of coal during the\nwinter increased his expenses the\ncommission upheld the rate.\nAccording to Assistant Arbiter\nPaul H. Pressintin, this ruling do.es\nnot conflict with the decision of the\ncivil courts under which the rent\nof a tenant cannot be increased\nafter winter coal is delivered.\nFive rent reductions were ordered\nby the commission yesterday.\n6 FLEE TO SAFETY AS\nEAST SIDE FLAT BURNS\nSix persons, including four small\nchildren, werp forced to flee to the\nstreet in their night clothes, early\ntoday, when a flat occupied by\nGeorge M. Dyke and Fred Middle\nton, 685 Maryland Ave., was dam\naged by fire. The fire was discov\nered shortly after 2 a. m., when Mr.\nand Mrs. Dyke were awakened by\nsmoke. Dyke discovered the base\nment ablaze. Unable to get to the\nrear of the basement, he awakened\nhis three small children and the\nMiddletons. The cause of the fire is\nunknown.\nFIRST RUSS ORLOFFS TO\nBE AT POULTRY SHOW\nRussian Orloffs will be exhibited\nfor the first time in Milwaukee at.\nthe exhibit of the National Poultry\nAssn, in the Auditorium, Nov. 24\nto 29, according to a statement\nby local chicken fanciers today. Mrs.\nMichael Werner, 735 39th St., wife\nof the policeman on duty in Mayor\nDaniel W. Hoan\u2019s office, is the\nowner of three chickens of this\nbreed which will be exhibited.\nNUGENT SANITARIUM\nMADE HOME FOR BLIND\nThe Nugent sanatarium, Hawley\nRd. and Wells St., will be utilized as\na Home for the Blind, according to\nofficials of the convention bureau,\nCommerce Assn., today.\nIt is proposed to make Dec. 12\nBlind Sunday in all churches of the\nstate, when delegations of young\nwomen will solicit contributions In\naid of the \"lighthouse\u2019\u2019 project.\nJUVENILE COURT\nREFLECTS DROP\nIN EMPLOYMENT\nHome Work and Wages Re\nduced, Say Mothers.\nIncreased unemployment was re\nflected in the number of women ask\ning for county aid in juvenile court,\ntoday.\nIn several cases where women had\nreceived aid in the past, the amounts\nwere increased because the appli\ncants declared they were unable to\nsupport themselves and their fam\nilies since they were thrown out of\nwork.\nOne of the women stated that she\nhad been doing home work for the\nPhoenix Knitting Co., but that her\nemployment ceased last week. In\nanother instance a mother of three\nchildren stated that her weekly\nwages had been reduced. Her story\nrevealed that she had been aband\noned.\nNinety per cent of all children\nborn blind are In this condition as a\nresult of sex disease in the parents,\naccording to a statement made in\njuvenile court in connection with the\ncase of a divorced woman with a\nchild whose father was said to be a\nsoldier. The right eye of the baby\nis in very bad condition. Both\nmother and child were ordered to\nthe county hospital.\nAngeline, aged 15, who admitted\nhaving kept company with a mar\nried man, was placed under proba\ntion in juvenile court today. Testi\nmony was offered that the parents\nof the girl were more to blame than\nthe girl herself. Probation officer\nstated that the family of nine Is liv\ning in four rooms with two board\ners quartered in the home.\nDETECTIVE GOES TO\nCHICAGO TO IDENTIFY\nLOOT UPON SUSPECT\nIn an effort to identify loot found\non Christ Rohrer by Chicago police,\na local sleuth today was sent to\nChicago. The articles are believed\nto have been taken when Rohrer is\nalleged to have entered the home of\nMrs. Florence Johnson, 294 15th St.,\nand locked her sister, Mrs. George\nParkinson, in a pantry, when she\nsurprised him.\nA woman, who gave her name as\nBertha. Steinmetz, Chicago, was -ar\nrested with Rohrer. He is believed\nto be the \u201cperfume burglar\u201d who\nhas been operating in Milwaukee.\nA man who claims his home is in\nMilwaukee is held by Waukegan, 111.,\nofficials, in connection with a hold\nup staged in that city Wednesday.\nHe gave the name of Lawrence\nPolzin, 20, and said he lived on Lap\nham St.\n\u2019PHONE CO. ENGINEERS\nDISCUSS RADIO \u2019PHONE\nEngineers of the Wisconsin Tele\nphone Co. are discussing a new\nportable radio-telephone which it is\nclaimed has brought the pocket tele\nphone a step nearer realization.\nOfficials of the company declared to\nday the matter is still In Its infancy\nand little could be said at present\nas to its application. Assembling of\nthe necessary radiophone apparatus\ninto a compact unit having a weight\nof about 60 pounds is one of the\nfeatures of the invention, according\nto Popular Mechanics magazine.\nUnder ordinary conditions it is said\nthe new instrument may be depend\ned on to operate satisfactorily over\ndistances of from 5 to 15 miles.\nTOOK DEPOSITS; FAILED\nJO GIVE SUITS; JAILED\nTweAty-five witnesses were In dis\ntrict court Friday <o complain\nagainst Charles Kann^kis, tailor at\n287 Reed St. They testified that\nthey made deposits on suits but that\nthe tailor refused to make them\nafter he got the money. Kannekis\nbought the tailor shop July f* from\nMat Sarino who claims he never re\nceived his money. He was sentenced\nto three months in the house of cor\nrection on the charge of larceny by\ntrick.\nAUTOIST GOES INTO\nWOHO FLEES\nCrashes Into Auto Shop; Po\nlice Seek Dane Man.\nThe police are searching for an\nautoist who crashed through the\nshow window of the Chevrolet Motor\nCo., 11th St. and Grand Ave., early\ntoday. The. driver of the car, evi\ndently a stranger, after the crash\ninto the window he backed his can,\noft the sidewalk and continued west\non Grand Ave. John Black, 503\nSycamore St., a witness to the acci\ndent, informed the police that the\nlicense number was 15,502. Accord\ning to the records the car is owned\nby E. C. Welch, Dane, Wis.\nEdward Schmagel received a frac\ntured leg when the motorcycle he\nwas riding crashed into a tree on the\nHawley Rd., near Grand Ave. Mike\nCrowley, a 'companion, also was\nslightly injured. Both men were\ntaken to the Emergency.\nHenry Klempa, 46, was killed late\nyesterday when caught between a\ncoach and a post. He was coupling\nan air hose in the Milwaukee road\nyards.\nFrank Hahn, 2429 Oakland St.,\nwas fined $25 in district*court on the\ncharge of reckless driving. It is al\nleged that he crashed into the auto\nof Peter Bloom Nov. 11 at 30tfl and\nCenter Sts.\nCharles Hirsch and Peter Schnei\nder were each fined SSO on the same\ncharge.\nAn unidentified man, about 50,\nwas found dead along the Milwaukee\nrailroad Friday, a half mile west of\nthe Main St. crossing, Wauwatosa.\nGeorge Baltes, chief of police, noti\nfied the coroner. The man was evi\ndently struck by a train while walk\ning along the tracks, Baltes says. He\nwore working clothes.\nRubin Marsland, age 36, 750 Na\ntional Ave., was injured shortly be\nfore noon while at work at the\nWisconsin Bridge and Iron Co. He\nsuffered contusion of the shoulder,\nfracture of the ribs when a pile of\nlumber fell on him,\nTHE MILWAUKEE LEADER\nBUCKING THE LINE\nMX 07'TTX\nThe bell, not the hammer, for\nMilwaukee engineers, who decided\nlast night to boost Milwaukee,\nBELIEVES\u2122\nJURYWEIGHINb\nBOOZEHUNNING\nFive Hurley Witnesses Are\nCalled Before Probers.\nFurther probing into the causes\nof and the connection Milwaukee has\nwith the Hurley rum smuggling and\nkilling, occupied the federal grand\njury today, it is believed.\nThe five Hurley witnesses, who\narrived here late Wednesday and\nwere before the jury the greater part\nof yesterday, again were present in\nthe federal building today. United\nStates District Attorney H. H. Saw\nyer, for the first time since the jury\nwent into session four weeks ago,\nappeared before that body today.\nFamiliar among local saloonists\nwho came and testified were Joseph\nA. Budar, Joseph Kurtz and J. B.\nOlllnger. It is also believed that\nHarry W. Arnold, wholesale liquor\ndealer, who lost 350 cases of whisky\nwhen prohibition agents raided the\nwarehouse of the United Fire Proof\nWarehouse Co., 3^2 Prospect Ave.,\nseveral weeks ago, testified before\nthe jury.\nThe jury is expected to vote an\nadjournment until next Tuesday, latj\ntoday.\nBELGiAKTLABOR CRISIS\nEXPECTED BY EDUCATOR\nSpecial to The header.\nSEATTLE, Wash. \u2014Dr. Henri De-\nMan, who is on his way east and\nwill sail in December for Belgium\nto resume his old work of director\nof labor education, said on leaving\nSeattle that he expected a crisis to\nbe reached between the Belgian gov\nernment and labor in the very near\nfuture. \u201cReconstruction following\nthe war is over and the inevitable\nconflict again appears,\u201d he said. \u201cIt\nis only a question of time when the\nLabor party will withdraw from .the\ncoalition government and become\nagain the opposition. A labor gov\nernment in Belgium, based on an ac\ntual majority vote, could carry on a\nlot of gradual and experimental so\ncialization in one line, after another.\u201d\nSOVIET RELIEF BOARD\nBRANDS CHARGE FALSE\nSpecial to The Leader.\nWASHINGTON\u2014The Central Sov\niet Russia Medical Relief committee,\nNew York, in a statement to the\nsoviet bureau, New York, brands as\nfalse accusations as to account re\ncently made against speakers and\norganizers of the Detroit branch of\nthe relief committee, and recom\nmends that the activities of the in\ndividuals responsible for such false\naccusations be disavowed.\nGIRL\u2019S ALLEGED SLAYER\nCAUGHT AFTER ESCAPE\nKEARNEY, Neb.\u2014Dennis Ches\nter, accused of killing Florence Bar\nton, Kansas City society girl, was\ncaptured four miles south of Oconto,\ntoday. He was taken to Broken Bow.\nChester was arrested In Montana and\nmade his escape frorq officers at\nBroken Bow Tuesday by jumping\nfrom the window of a moving train,\ns. walesTaborregime\nPROTESTS DEBS\u2019 JAILING\nSpecial to The Beader,\nSYDNEY, Australia \u2014The Austral\nian Labor party in conference at\nAdelaide (South Australia), passed\na motion, protesting the continued\nimprisonment of Eugene V. Debs,\nand asks that all labor bodies in\nAustralia join in a joint protest to\nthe United States department of\njustice.\nWAS MILWAUKEEIviAN\nCONFIDANT OF PRIEST\nNOW MUSEUM MUMMY?\n^^^^^Continued^romJFir&t Page.\nChrist. On the stucco, which is\nplaced around the cypress box, are\ninscribed the old Egyptian hiero\ngliphlcs and the awkward imitations\nof sacred beasts and all-powerful\n'gods. z\nThe body is that of a priest whose\nreligious name was \u201cSon of Pet\nAmon.\u201d He lived between 1740-\n1661 B. C.\nSaid Dr. Barrett:\nReincarnation, the doctrine that\nhuman souls can be reborn in non\nhuman bodies, is 'developed out of\nthree universal savage beliefs; 1,\nthat a man has a soul, connected\nin some vague way with the\nbreath that can be separated\nfrom his material, body, tempo\nrarily in sleep, permanently in\ndeath; 2, that animals and even\nplants have souls, and are pos\nsessed to a large etxent of human\npowers and passions; 3, that souls\ncan be transferred from one\norganism to another.\nSoul Passed to Animals.\nReincarnation teaches that at\ndeath the soul passes into another\nliving creature, man. animal or\neven plant.\nThe ancient Egyntian belief had\nit that after death the soul passed\nipto the body of one of the sacred\nanimals if the man had passed a\nworthy life, and then, after a s\nspecies of purification, into the\nbody of a human. If tne man had\npassed a worthless life, how\never, the soul went into one of\nthe beasts of burden.\nHELD FOR ROBBERY.\nCharles Brown, alias Dick Courtney, was\nbound over to municipal court for trial\non a charge of assault and robbery. Bail\nwas placed at $2,000. It is alleged that\nhe assaulted and robbed Peter Bialek, who\nwas asleep in his bunk on Pere Marquette\ncar ferry No. 10, Wednesday night, of $l6O.\nB\nWomen in the world of commerce\nare being buttonholed today by their\nprofessional sisters. The Milwaukee\nBusiness Women\u2019s club, at its meet\ning last night, decided on an inten\nsive campaign for new members.\n(Five hundred is the limit set.\nNormalites Shown\nImproper Dances\nProf. G. M. Caskey, director of the\nCaskey Dancing school, 69 Wisconsin\nSt., and Mrs. Margaret Nicholls, of\nthe physical training department\nMilwaukee State Normal school,\ngive a demonstration on improper\ndances before students and faculty\nof the normal school ifi the assem\nbly hall this morning.\nAmong the dances was the\ncat dance, just originated. This\nGIRL, 16, MISSING\nWITH WEAVER OF\nROMANTIC TALES\nDisappearance Is Revealed\nWhen Father Asks Warrant.\nJessie Loomis, aged 16, dreamer\nof romances, Is missing from her\ncountry home near Hales Corners.\nGone, too, is Frank Markolowsky,\naged 27, wounded world war veteran,\nneighbor and weaver of colorful\ntales of old world cities and adven\nture.\nThe disappearance of the pair was\nrevealed, late yesterday, with the\n\u2019swearing out of a warrant for Mar\nkolowsky by Charles Loomis, father\nof the girl, charging the former sol\ndier with abduction.\nMarkolowsky lost a leg in the war\narid came to live with his father\nWhile recovering.\nThe girl\u2019s parents say she seemed\ncontented at home until the romantic\nsoldier came. She took no clothes\nwith her and the shoes she had were\nvery poor.\nOn the night the couple disap\npeared, Frank bought a pair of girl\u2019s\nshoes at Hales Corners saying they\nwere for his sister. He had received\nhis check from the government that\nday.\nFrank has been a frequent caller\nat the Loomis home since he has re\nturned from the war. He has trav\neled much in this country, also\nFrance and Hawaii and told many\ninteresting tales of his travels which\nJessie Was always much interested\nIn, says the girl\u2019s father.\nENGLISH NOVELIST TO\nTELL MILWAUKEEANS\nWHY PERSONS MARRY\nWhy get married, will be one of\nthe things explained by W. L. George,\nEnglish novelist in his lecture be\nfore the /Milwaukee Open Forum,\nTuesday, 8 p. m., In Wisconsin Con\nservatory of Music hall, 440 Milwau\nkee St.\n\u201cMr. George,\u201d says the advance\nannouncement, \"will explain the na\nture and origin of love. He will tell\nwhy it arises and why it so often\nfalls. He has made an intensive\nstudy of scores of marriages, includ\ning his own, and is regarded as one\nof the world\u2019s leading authorities on\nthe subject.\n\u201cIn his talk, Mr. George will deal\nwith what he calls \u2018the gentlest art,\u2019\nnamely, the management of mar\nriage. He will show, that marriage\ndeprives people of freedom and ad\nventure, but is \u2018the only insurance\npolicy against loneliness.\u201d\nMRS. BRINKMAN, BOTH\nLEGS SHATTERED, SHOWS\nIMPROVEMENT, IS CLAIM\nHow Mrs. Viola Brinkman can\ncontinue to live after her flight from\nthe third floor through the aeraway\nof the county jail last Tuesday, in\nan attempt at suicide, Is a niystery\nto jail officials and physicians at\ntending her at the County \"hospital.\nDoctors in the County hospital this\nmorning reported Mrs. Brinkman\u2019s\ncondition as better. Both her legs,\nbadly splintered and bruised, can,\nwith the aid of modern science, be\nmade as good as new, physicians\nsaid. Whether Mrs. Brinkman has\nsustained any serious internal in\njuries cannot as yet be determined.\nMrs. Brinkmankwas in the county\njail awaiting trial on the charge of\nshooting and killing her husband.\nJack Brinkman, in the St. Charles\nhotel last August.\nAnnouncement!\nWe have transferred the ex\nclusive distribution rights\nof the\n\u201cMALTINA\nTON\u201d\nFor the States of Wisconsin\nand lowa to Mr. Herman\nClaus Reimers, and all fu\nture orders should be sent\nto the\nH.C. REIMERS CO.\n404 HARMON ST.\nMILWAUKEE, WIS.\nSince Oct. 25, 1920,\nMaltina Co., Chicago, 111.,\nG. A. Heine, Manager.\nI\nMembers of the Marquette Wom\nen\u2019s league probably will put on\ntheir heavy wraps in, preparation for\noutdoor activities such as they have\nnot participated in in years. The\norganization, yesterday, voted to\nfoster the boy scout movement.\ndance requires a special form of ffiu\nslc \u2014slow and feline as the name of\nthe dance suggests.\nThe dancers also gave exhibitions\nof the Fox trot, one step and waltz.\nProf. Caskey advised the students\nagainst freak movements and spec\ntacular ball room dancing.\nHe asked that they adopt con\nservative and dignified positions on\nthe dance floor.\nNew Hand Stove\nIs Discovered by\nMarquette Co-eds\nA new hand stove has been dis\ncovered at Marquette, says The\nMarquette Tribunal; the univer\nsity\u2019s official weekly.\nSays The \u201cTrlb\u201d:\nThe newly discovered heater\nwill be used for the first time dur\ning the North Dakota-Marauette\ngame Nov. 20. It will be used\nagain by the co-eds who will go\nto Indianapolis for the game with\nWabash college. Thanksgiving\nday. They are confident that\nsomewhere in Indianapolis they\nwill be able to find the raw ma\nterial for a heater.\nThereafter it will be used on\nhikes, sleighrides, auto drives.\nThe heater, the hand stove dis\ncovered Jjy Marquette co-eds is\u2014\na baked potato. The girls affirm\nthat the jacket keeps heat from\nescaping for a long time, and that\na baked potato in each pocket of\na winter coat is an efficient means\nof preventing cold hands.\nLEAD BY HUSBAND TO\n$5 FINE FOR SHOPLIFTING\nMrs. Mabel Cenles, 1019 State \u00aet.,\nwas arrested In a downtown depart\nment store where she had stolen\nsilks valued at $lB. Her case was\nfilled yesterday in district court,\nbut she failed to appear and she was\nbrought in this morning by her hus\nband. _\nENTIRE STOCK\nMUST BE SOLD\nTHE COLUMBIA PANTS CO.\n1339 GREEN BAY AVE.\nWill sacrifice 12,685 pair of Men\u2019s and\nYoung Men\u2019s High Grade Trousers at\n50c on the dollar and less.\nSale Starts SATURDAY, November 20\nHere is your'greatest opportunity to save as you never\nsaved before. If you have an old coat come to this sale\u2014\nwe will match a pair of pants and save you buying a suit.\nHundreds of patterns to select from. Remember the CO\nLUMBIA is an exclusive Men\u2019s Pants Store and the only\none of its kind in the city. Price and quality will be for\ngotten during this week. It will be a genuine bargain feast\nand well worth your journey of many miles to come and\nbuy 2 and 3 pair at these low prices.\nSale Starts Saturday, Nov. 20\u2014Rain or Shine\nAT 1339 GREEN BAY AVE\n$3.50 Men\u2019s Work Trousers\n\u2014dark patterns. All sizes,\nnow\u2014\n-51.69\n\u00a75.00 Men\u2019s and Young\nMen\u2019s High Grade Pants\nat\u2014\n52.95\nFriday, November 19. 1920\nNo need erf bare tables here\nThanksgiving, unless you are broke.\nDealers report 175,000 pounds of\npoultry in storage.\nHEFUSALTOOK\nSWTS MUSES\nWORDLESSNESS\nB. S. BOBROFF.\nCould Get $80,000,000 of\n^Russ Business, Claim.\nSteady employment for all work\ners in Milwaukee this winter and\nperhaps for years to come is being\nthwarted by the United States gov\nernment, because of its refusal to\nrecognize soviet Russia, according to\nannouncement today by B. JL. Bob\nroff, head of the Bobroff Foreign\nTrading and Engineering Co., Ma\njestic Bldg.\n\"At present businessmen of this\ncity have contracts with Russians for\n$6,000,000 worth of machines, ma\nchine tools and ord\u2019nary tools, and\n$2,000,000 worth of men\u2019s working\nshoe,\u201d said Bobroff; \u201cThe delivery of\nmaterial under these contracts is be\ning held up because the govern\nment refuses to accept Russian gold\nfor American dollars. We could get\n10 times this amount of business,\nand more yet with the Russian gov\nernment if it were not the govern\nmertt\u2019s attitude.\n\"It is possible to contract with the\nRussians for at least $80,000,000\nthe thousands of Milwaukee workers\nworth of business. This would give\nwork throughout the winter and per\nhaps for years to come, instead of\nletting them walk the streets, which\nseems to be inevitable. All this can\nbe hinged directly onto the attitude\nof the government in restricting the\ntreasury department from respecting\nRussian gold.\u201d\nPOSTOFFICE TO BE CLOSED\nALL .DAY THANKSGIVING\nThe Milwaukee postoffice will be\nclosed all day Thanksgiving day,\nNov. 25, Postmaster Frank Schutz\nannounced today. All substations\nwill be shut and there will be no de\nliveries, Schutz said.\nMilwaukee\u2019s school children are\njubilant at the prospect of closed\nschools from Wednesday of next i\nweek until the Monday following I\nThanksgiving.\nAT 1339 GREEN BAY AVE.j\n\u00a74.00 Men\u2019s Extra Heavy\nWork or Dress Pants now\n$1.98\n\u00a77.50 All Wool Pants\u2014\nhundreds of pairs to select\nfrom, now\u2014\n-53.85\nAT 1339 GREEN BAY AVEJS\nm poms\nOF POULTRY IN\nSTORAGE HERE\nHeld for Holiday Rusli, Say\nCommission Men.\nMilwaukee has over 175,000\npounds of dressed poultry in cold\nstorage awaiting the Thanksgiving\nand Christmas demand.\nThis, today, was the statement or\nmanagers of cold storage plants in\nthe city.\nHenry Mueller, superintendent of\nthe storage plant, George Mansfield\nCo., asserted his concern is now stor\ning 100,000 pounds of poultry in pre\nparation for the demand within the\nnext few weeks.\n\"We are holding that amount to\nmeet the great demand for poultry\nduring the latter part of November\nand December,\u201d he said. \u201cIt has\nalways been customary to store this\namount at this time of the year. It\nalso depends a great deal on weather\nconditions. If the weather is cold\nmany of the butchers store their own\nfowl, but if it is warm the poultry\nis placed in cold storage.\u201d\n\u201cPoultry is stored in large quanti\nties now because a sudden demand\nfor dressed fowl will have to be met\nwithin the next few weeks,\u201d said Ed\nward* Thomas, superintendent, Wis\ncon.sin Cold Storage Co. \"There un\ndoubtedly is about 175,000 stored\nthroughout the city.\n\u201cThis must be done or the demand\nfor poultry would never be met.\nThis is the poultry season and it is\nnow that it must be saved for future\nconsumption.\u201d\nCharles Kramer, deputy state\nfood and dairy inspector, corrobo\nrated the statements of the storage\nj men. He also asserted that it is\nnecessary to store poultry now in\norder that there will be enough on\nhand when the holiday season be\ngins. He denied that this storage\ncreates an artificial shortage.\nDOCTOR ADVOCATES\nUSE OF X-RAY TO FIT\nFOOTWEAR PROPERLY\nUse of X-ray machines as a means\nof properly fitting shoes would\nj eliminate many cases of crippled\n[feet and corns and bunions, accord\ning to a statement today by Dr.\nWilliam F. Hilger, Roentgen expert.\nThe X-ray Is capable of showing the\nexact position of the foot within the\nshoe and whether or not there Is\ncramping, according to the phy-.\nsician.\n\u201cWith this machine\u201d the doctor\nj said, \u201cevery bone is outlined, and,\nby comparison with the picture of\nthe feet in their natural state, tt\ncan be determined without doubt\nwhether the bones of the feet are\ndistorted or restricted by the shoe.\nThe device will not only settle any\ncontroversy which may arise, as to\nproper size, but will also show, with\nout leaving chance for argument,\nwhether a shoe is of correct design\nor shape.\u201d\n\u00a74.50 Men\u2019s Neat Striped Pants\n\u2014well made. Sizes 28 to 42,\nn 0\n52.29\n4\n\u00a79.00 \u00a7IO.OO Pants of all wool,\nworsteds and cassimeres. Dark\nand light patterns, n 0\n54.65\nTWO\n*AT 1339 GREEN BAY AVE.S","height":"28116","width":"22077"}}
